	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>This is an interesting model but I think there are some dissapointing things which are no doubt likely to surface due to it. The most significant is the cheapening of the 'loot aspect'. Horizons' great failure was no provide neither loot or pvp, and wasn't able to keep people interested for very long due to this. <br />
<br />
Games with a pay-for-loot model will likely suffer a similar, if less epidemic, effect when players find that effort in game to acquire new stuff: playing for more stuff becomes meaningless. The majority of high power chars in EQ that are bought and not uberguilded are quickly thrown into a pattern of being rotated amongst new owners. I tracked 5 different owners all applying to my guild, of the same character, in 6 months. A decent minority, though, does indeed benefit from buying stuff- but there's a reason it's a minority! This is because the majority of the playerbase doesn't find buying stuff that should be a natural course of a video game to be enjoyable. <br />
<br />
One of the main driving forces to play in mmgorpgs is to progress- ie, progress levels, loot, and the uber guild progression. When this can be bought, there's less reason to play.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
